# Hong Kong's Position as an International Financial Centre

The HKMA achieved significant progress in 2024 in strengthening Hong Kong's position as a globally competitive international financial centre.

HKMA collaborates with relevant authorities in Mainland China and Hong Kong to roll out a series of measures to deepen and expand the interconnectedness between Hong Kong and Mainland China’s financial markets, including optimizing the ‘Cross-boundary WMC’; expanding the Hong Kong dollar liquidity arrangements and the qualified collateral scope for ‘Northbound Bond Connect’; enhancing ‘Northbound Bond Connect’; and optimizing the Primary Liquidity Provider Scheme. These initiatives help reinforce Hong Kong’s role as a gateway and consolidate its status as a major offshore renminbi hub.

HKMA has also made good progress in consolidating Hong Kong’s financial platform competitiveness across areas such as bond issuance, asset and wealth management, green and sustainable finance, and corporate treasury centres. To promote Hong Kong’s financial services, HKMA has enhanced outreach efforts toward overseas and Mainland stakeholders, showcasing the resilience of Hong Kong’s financial system and the opportunities it offers. The successful hosting of the third ‘Global Financial Leaders’ Investment Summit’ and other major events not only enhances Hong Kong’s image as a leading international financial centre but also creates positive ripple effects. HKMA actively participates in multiple international and regional central banking and regulatory organizations, continuing its efforts to maintain financial stability and promote market development globally.

In terms of ‘Fintech 2025’ strategy, HKMA has made notable progress, particularly in areas like central bank digital currencies and data infrastructure.

The registration count and transaction volume of the Faster Payment System (FPS) continued to grow steadily, reaching 15.8 million registrations by the end of 2024, with daily average real-time HKD transactions rising to 1.65 million. HKMA is working closely with the People’s Bank of China to promote the implementation of cross-border payments via FPS and the Mainland’s Online Payment Cross-Bank Clearing System.

# Overview

In 2024, HKMA continued to strive to enhance Hong Kong’s competitiveness as an international financial centre.

HKMA expanded and optimized the interoperability mechanisms with Mainland China, helping to reinforce Hong Kong’s role as a bridge between Mainland and international markets. During the year, several improvements related to ‘Cross-boundary WMC’ were introduced to facilitate cross-border investment by individuals within the Greater Bay Area (GBA). In February, HKMA included in the eligible collateral list for RMB liquidity arrangements onshore Chinese government bonds and policy bank-issued financial bonds. In July, authorities from both sides announced further support for overseas investors using bonds held via Bond Connect as collateral for ‘Northbound Bond Connect’ transactions, which commenced implementation in January 2025. Additionally, ‘Northbound Bond Connect’ was optimized during the year, increasing flexibility and efficiency in hedging strategies and portfolio management.

Hong Kong’s offshore renminbi business continued to grow robustly in 2024. Measures to enhance the Primary Liquidity Provider arrangement, such as increasing the number of providers and expanding the scheme’s size, were implemented. By year’s end, the night-time cross-border service capacity of the HKD Real Time Gross Settlement System was upgraded to better meet global cross-border renminbi payment needs.

HKMA launched several initiatives under GBA financial co-operation, including pilot projects for cross-border credit referencing to facilitate cross-border corporate financing, and cross-boundary remittance and payment arrangements for Hong Kong residents purchasing property in the GBA.

HKMA remains dedicated to boosting Hong Kong’s overall financial platform competitiveness. To enhance Hong Kong’s attractiveness as a preferred fund management hub and family office centre, HKMA worked closely with the government and industry to create a more favorable tax and regulatory environment. Furthermore, HKMA issued the second batch of tokenized bonds under the Evergreen project, and launched the ‘EvergreenHub’, a one-stop digital bond knowledge base, along with the ‘Digital Bonds Grant Scheme’ — continuing to foster innovation in the Hong Kong bond market. In October, HKMA announced its ‘Sustainable Finance Action Plan’, setting specific targets to further solidify Hong Kong’s standing as a regional green and sustainable finance hub.

Meanwhile, HKMA continued to expand market outreach efforts to promote Hong Kong’s financial services overseas and on the Mainland. In November, HKMA hosted the third ‘Global Financial Leaders’ Investment Summit,’ a three-day event themed ‘Navigating Amid Change,’ attracting top industry leaders from over 120 international financial institutions. The summit was opened by the Vice Premier of the State Council, Mr. Han Zheng, followed by sessions led by three Mainland financial regulators and discussions involving international financial leaders, demonstrating strong support and confidence in Hong Kong from the global financial community.

During the year, HKMA also organized various seminars and conferences, including:
- the joint Climate Finance Conference with the Dubai Financial Services Authority in September;
- the 15th Global Risk Forum with the Global Association of Risk Professionals in October;
- the International Financial Seminar with BIS in October; and
- the Financial Stability Board Plenary Meeting in December — the first such meeting held in Asia since 2016, gathering leaders and senior officials from over 50 countries’ financial regulators and 12 international standard-setting bodies.

HKMA also actively strengthened bilateral ties with other regions. In December, HKMA held bilateral meetings with the Central Bank of the United Arab Emirates (CBUAE) and the Central Bank of Saudi Arabia in Hong Kong, promoting investment and financial market linkages between the Middle East and Asia. HKMA signed a MoU with CBUAE to establish connectivity between their debt capital market infrastructures, facilitating cross-border debt securities issuance and investment activities. In October, HKMA visited Doha, Qatar, to deepen cooperation in financial services.

Furthermore, in December, HKMA held its seventh Hong Kong–Switzerland Financial Dialogue, covering regional and local outlooks, policy challenges, and the latest developments and cooperation opportunities in sustainable finance, fintech, and market connectivity.

HKMA’s visits to Thailand and Malaysia in January and May, respectively, strengthened ties with central banks, financial institutions, and enterprises, promoting Hong Kong’s position as an international financial centre and expanding bilateral cooperation—focusing on RMB and domestic currency cross-border investment and trade settlement, and showcasing Hong Kong’s competitive advantages.

On the international stage, HKMA actively participates in central banking affairs and continues to play leadership roles in several regional and global committees. HKMA currently serves as co-chair of the Basel Committee’s Policy and Standards Sub-Group and the Regional Consultative Group for Asia under the Financial Stability Board. It is also co-chair of the FSB’s Financial Innovation Network (until July 2024). HKMA has chaired the Executives’ Meeting of East Asia-Pacific Central Banks (EMEAP) Financial Markets Working Group since 2018, serving multiple terms through 2024.

HKMA’s Financial Technology Facilitation Office and banking departments continue to implement the ‘Fintech 2025’ strategy, promoting wider adoption of fintech and strengthening Hong Kong’s role as a hub for digital finance in Asia. Key initiatives in 2024 include:
- advancing fintech applications across five major areas: wealthtech, insurtech, green tech, AI, and distributed ledger technology;
- promoting central bank digital currency development, including:
    - advancing the ‘mBridge’ cross-border CBDC project to improve cross-border payments;
    - further studying the feasibility of issuing a ‘Digital Hong Kong Dollar’ (e-HKD) in Hong Kong;
    - exploring the development of a tokenisation market supported by CBDCs;
- enhancing SME lending via the ‘Commercial Data Interchange’;
- strengthening cross-border fintech cooperation; and
- promoting wider use of the FPS.

Use of FPS in 2024 continued to rise, with registrations and transaction volumes increasing steadily over the past six years. By end-2024, there were 15.8 million registrations, with daily real-time HKD transaction count up by 33% year-on-year. Aside from steady growth in person-to-person and business payments, the increase was driven by government bill payments, merchant payments, and top-ups for e-wallets and bank accounts, sustaining the growth trend.

To ensure the safety and efficiency of Hong Kong’s retail payments industry, HKMA monitors six designated retail payment systems under the Payment Systems and Stored Value Facilities Ordinance (PSSVFO), and supervises 15 licensed stored value facilities (four issued by licensed banks). During the year, HKMA worked closely with industry stakeholders to strengthen controls and safeguard consumers amid rising scam risks.

In February, HKMA and the Financial Services and the Treasury Bureau completed a two-month public consultation on proposed legislation for stablecoin issuer regulation, issuing a joint consultation summary in July, and submitting the ‘Stablecoins Bill’ to LegCo in December. To better understand issuer business models and develop appropriate regulatory frameworks, HKMA launched a stablecoin issuer ‘sandbox’, announcing three participants into the scheme in July. Concurrently, HKMA continues to actively participate in international organizations’ work on digital assets—including stablecoins and tokenisation—to ensure the related regulation aligns with international standards and best practices.

# Summary of HKMA’s Measures in 2024 to Strengthen Hong Kong’s Competitiveness as an International Financial Centre

Deepening interconnection with Mainland China markets to solidify Hong Kong’s role as an offshore renminbi hub and enhance GBA links:
- Optimizing ‘Cross-boundary WMC’ and ‘Northbound Bond Connect’;
- Expanding the HKMA RMB liquidity arrangements and collateral scope to include onshore RMB bonds issued by the Ministry of Finance and Mainland policy banks;
- Improving the Primary Liquidity Provider arrangement;
- Upgrading the HKD Real Time Gross Settlement System’s night-time cross-border capabilities to better support global cross-border RMB payments;
- Supporting issuance of Dim Sum bonds for Shenzhen, Guangdong, and Hainan governments in Hong Kong;
- Facilitating cross-border financing through credit referencing pilots;
- Implementing cross-border remittance measures within the GBA property market;
- Deepening exchanges and communication with Mainland authorities and industry to explore new opportunities.

Enhancing global connectivity:
- Hosting key international events: ‘Global Financial Leaders’ Investment Summit,’ FSB Plenary, and BIS collaborative seminars;
- Promoting Hong Kong’s financial services overseas and in Mainland China, establishing cooperative foundations with the Middle East and ASEAN regions;
- Engaging actively in international and regional central banking and regulatory forums.

Strengthening competitiveness of financial platform:
- Advancing bond market innovation via Evergreen project, including the issuance of the world’s first multi-currency digital bonds;
- Launching EvergreenHub, a one-stop digital bond knowledge hub;
- Continuing to promote digital bonds and the Digital Bonds Grant Scheme.
